","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8827"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49480"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1243"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"6132"},{"type":"tags","id":"6281"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29708"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43610"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64049"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with ongoing left shoulder pain and reduced function four months after sustaining a rotator cuff tear while playing football. The diagnosis was confirmed with an ultrasound showing a partial thickness tear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works full-time as an architect and remains fully independent with all activities of daily living. He has completed a course of physiotherapy but continues to have symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is reduced range of movement in the left shoulder consistent with a rotator cuff tear. There is no muscle wasting or neurological deficit.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate timeframe for surgical referral if symptoms persist despite conservative management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["After six weeks of conservative management","Immediate referral","After 12 months of conservative management","There is no role for surgical management","After six months of conservative management"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a partial thickness rotator cuff tear with ongoing symptoms despite initial conservative management. The timing of surgical referral depends on several factors including age, mechanism of injury, tear size, and response to conservative treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAfter six months of conservative management\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate timeframe for surgical referral if symptoms persist. This allows adequate time to assess response to non-operative treatment while not delaying unnecessarily if surgery is ultimately needed. Conservative management should include physical therapy, activity modification, and appropriate pain management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate referral\u003C/strong\u003E would only be appropriate for acute, traumatic full-thickness tears in young patients, or in cases with significant weakness or functional impairment. This patient\u0027s partial thickness tear does not meet these criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAfter six weeks\u003C/strong\u003E of conservative management is too early to determine treatment failure, as many patients continue to improve with ongoing physiotherapy and rehabilitation during this period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAfter 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E of conservative management represents an unnecessarily long delay if symptoms have not improved after six months, potentially leading to further muscle atrophy and poorer surgical outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EStating there is \u003Cstrong\u003Eno role for surgical management\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While many partial thickness tears can be managed conservatively, surgery may be appropriate in cases that fail to respond to adequate conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe decision for surgery should be based on factors including persistent pain, functional limitation, failure of conservative management, and patient factors such as age, activity level, and occupation. The six-month timeframe represents a balance between allowing adequate time for conservative management while not delaying appropriate surgical intervention when needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Conservative management is first-line treatment for rotator cuff tears and should be trialled for at least 6 months before considering surgery.","Surgical referral is appropriate when there is failure of conservative management or in young patients with acute, traumatic full-thickness tears.","Physical therapy focusing on strengthening and range of motion exercises is essential in conservative management of rotator cuff tears."],"references":["Kim YS, Lee HJ, Kim JH, Noh DY. When Should We Repair Partial-Thickness Rotator Cuff Tears? Outcome Comparison Between Immediate Surgical Repair Versus Delayed Repair After 6-Month Period of Nonsurgical Treatment. Am J Sports Med. 2018 Apr;46(5):1091-1096. doi: 10.1177/0363546518757425. Epub 2018 Mar 5. PMID: 29505742. Available online at ; https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29505742/","Longo UG, Lalli A, Medina G, Maffulli N. Conservative management of partial thickness rotator cuff tears: a systematic review. Sports Medicine and Arthroscopy Review. 2023 Sep 1;31(3):80-7. Available online at ; https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Nicola-Maffulli/publication/375720918_Conservative_Management_of_Partial_Thickness_Rotator_Cuff_Tears_A_Systematic_Review/links/65781ca16610947889bb2e9b/Conservative-Management-of-Partial-Thickness-Rotator-Cuff-Tears-A-Systematic-Review.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49480"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16136"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49480"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T21:39:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T21:41:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8827"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64049"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"item